    brief: "Government decisions about spending levels and taxation, used to influence aggregate demand and stabilize the economy.",
    more: "Expansionary fiscal policy (higher G or lower T) raises aggregate demand and is used to combat recessions. Contractionary fiscal policy (lower G or higher T) reduces aggregate demand and is used to control inflation or reduce deficits. Fiscal policy operates with significant time lags: recognition, decision, and implementation lags can mean stimulus arrives after recovery has begun.",
    detailed: "Fiscal policy is more powerful when monetary policy is constrained, for example at the zero lower bound, because the interest rate channel of crowding out is inactive. Its effectiveness is stronger when automatic stabilizers are large, reducing the need for discretionary decisions. The ongoing debate between Keynesian and supply-side approaches centers on whether tax cuts or spending increases produce larger multipliers, and whether short-run demand stimulus comes at the cost of long-run supply-side damage through debt accumulation. Common mistake: Students assume fiscal and monetary policy always work in the same direction. When the Federal Reserve raises rates to offset fiscal stimulus, the net demand effect is ambiguous and depends on the relative sizes of the multiplier and the interest rate effect on investment.",
    seeAlso: ["monetary-policy", "automatic-stabilisers", "multiplier", "crowding-out", "budget-deficit"],
