    more: "The US has no federal VAT; indirect taxes include federal excise taxes on fuel, alcohol, and tobacco, alongside state and local sales taxes averaging around 7% nationally. Indirect taxes raise prices for consumers, shifting aggregate supply leftward when applied at scale. Their incidence is shared between producers and consumers depending on the relative price elasticities of demand and supply.",
    detailed: "Indirect taxes are generally regressive because lower-income households spend a larger fraction of their income on taxed goods and services. Governments use indirect taxes to internalize externalities (excise taxes on tobacco, carbon taxes on fuel) and to raise revenue with lower compliance costs than direct taxes. The tax incidence question is empirically important: a fuel tax whose full burden falls on commuters has different distributional effects than one whose incidence is shared with producers. Common mistake: Students assume the legal payer of an indirect tax bears its full burden. Incidence depends on elasticities: if demand is inelastic, consumers bear most of the tax; if supply is inelastic, producers absorb more.",
