    more: "The US federal income tax is progressive, with marginal rates ranging from 10% to 37% across seven brackets. Progressive taxation reduces income inequality and acts as an automatic stabilizer: higher earners pay proportionally more in booms and less in downturns, moderating the cycle.",
    detailed: "The progressivity of the overall US tax system is substantially less than the headline income tax rates suggest because FICA payroll taxes are regressive, capital gains are taxed at lower rates than wages, and many deductions disproportionately benefit higher earners. The trade-off in progressive taxation is between equity goals (redistributing income) and efficiency concerns (reducing incentives to work and invest as marginal rates rise). Supply-side economists emphasize the efficiency cost; Keynesian economists emphasize the redistribution benefit and the automatic stabilizer role. Common mistake: Students confuse marginal and average tax rates. A 37% top marginal rate does not mean top earners pay 37% of their total income; their average rate is considerably lower because only income above the top bracket threshold is taxed at 37%.",
