    brief: "Total government spending on goods and services, transfer payments, and debt interest, across federal, state, and local levels.",
    more: "Public expenditure is divided into current spending (public sector wages, healthcare, defense) and capital spending (infrastructure, public investment). Transfer payments (Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid, unemployment insurance) are the largest and fastest-growing components of federal spending and do not directly enter the AD equation but affect it through household consumption.",
    detailed: "The composition of public expenditure matters as much as its level for aggregate demand. Direct government purchases of goods and services have an immediate multiplier effect. Transfer payments depend on the MPC of recipients before feeding through to consumption. Capital expenditure on infrastructure can raise both short-run demand and long-run productive capacity, making it potentially the highest-return category of public spending. Common mistake: Students treat all public expenditure as equivalent in its aggregate demand effect. Transfer payments only affect AD to the extent recipients spend them; direct government purchases of goods have an immediate impact on national income.",
