    more: "FICA payroll taxes in the US are regressive: the Social Security portion applies only up to a wage base, so high earners pay a lower effective rate on total income. State sales taxes are also regressive because lower-income households spend a higher fraction of income on taxed goods and services.",
    detailed: "Regressive taxation increases income inequality by taking proportionally more from those who can least afford it. Governments often combine regressive indirect taxes with progressive direct taxes to achieve an overall tax mix that is moderately progressive in aggregate. The distributional impact of a tax reform requires analysis of the full system, not individual taxes in isolation. Common mistake: Students assume regressivity always reflects poor policy design. Regressive taxes may be chosen for efficiency reasons, such as targeting specific consumption behaviors, and their distributional impact can be offset through targeted transfer payments to lower-income households.",
