    more: "Cyclical components of the deficit disappear automatically as the economy recovers; the structural balance persists even at full employment. A structural deficit signals that the fiscal position is unsustainable in the long run without tax increases or spending cuts. The Congressional Budget Office (CBO) publishes structural balance estimates for the US.",
    detailed: "Measuring the structural balance requires estimating the output gap, which is unobservable and subject to significant revision, making structural balance calculations uncertain. Policymakers who focus on the structural balance avoid cutting spending in recessions solely because the deficit has widened cyclically. However, if the output gap is mismeasured, what appears to be a cyclical deficit may actually be structural, leading to an overly permissive fiscal stance. Common mistake: Students assume a cyclical deficit indicates sound fiscal management. A cyclical deficit can coexist with a structural deficit; only the structural balance reveals the underlying fiscal sustainability position.",
