    detailed: "The design of a tax system involves trade-offs between equity (fairness), efficiency (minimizing distortions to economic decisions), revenue adequacy (funding public services), and simplicity (minimizing compliance costs). A tax that is perfectly fair may be complex and economically distorting; a simple flat tax may be regressive. The Laffer curve argument that cutting tax rates can raise revenue by boosting economic activity has some theoretical merit but is empirically relevant only at very high marginal rates. Common mistake: Students assume higher taxes always reduce economic activity. Well-designed taxes that fund productive public investment can raise long-run growth; the net effect depends on the type of tax, the marginal rate, and how the revenue is spent.",
