    group: "Inflation",
    term: "Base effect",
    brief: "The distorting influence of the comparison period on year-on-year inflation figures, where an unusually high or low base causes inflation to appear to rise or fall without any current change in prices.",
    more: "If prices fell sharply one year ago, the same level of prices today produces a high year-on-year inflation reading simply because the comparison point is depressed. The base effect is mechanical: it reflects arithmetic, not underlying price pressure. The Federal Reserve monitors base effects closely when assessing whether inflation movements are transitory.",
    detailed: "Base effects are particularly important when interpreting headline inflation data during and after large shocks. During the 2021-22 inflation surge, early readings partly reflected the base of the pandemic price collapse in 2020; later readings reflected genuine underlying price pressures. Distinguishing base effects from structural inflation requires looking at month-on-month changes alongside year-on-year readings. Common mistake: Students treat a year-on-year inflation increase as always reflecting new price pressures. A high reading can be driven entirely by a low base period a year earlier, with prices flat or even falling in the current month.",
