    more: "The basket is updated periodically by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) to reflect changes in consumer purchasing behavior. Weights in the basket determine how much each category contributes to the overall index. Housing, transportation, and food account for the largest weights in the US CPI-U basket.",
    detailed: "The composition of the basket determines whose inflation the index measures. CPI-U covers urban consumers; CPI-W covers urban wage earners; PCE (used by the Fed for its 2% target) uses different weights derived from the national accounts that tend to show somewhat lower inflation than CPI. Substitution bias, quality improvements, and new goods all create potential for official indices to overstate or understate true price changes. Common mistake: Students treat CPI as measuring everyone's inflation equally. The basket reflects average urban consumer spending; a household that spends heavily on housing or healthcare may experience inflation well above the headline figure.",
