    more: "CPI-U is the most widely cited US inflation measure. The Federal Reserve uses Personal Consumption Expenditure (PCE) inflation for its 2% target, which tends to run slightly below CPI due to methodological differences. Core CPI strips out volatile food and energy prices to reveal underlying inflation trends.",
    detailed: "The difference between CPI and PCE matters for policy. PCE uses chain-weighting, allowing for substitution as consumers shift away from goods that become more expensive, which tends to produce lower readings than the fixed-weight CPI basket. PCE also has broader coverage of consumer spending, including third-party payments for healthcare such as Medicare and Medicaid. The Fed's preference for PCE over CPI is not arbitrary: PCE better captures the cost of living for a broad population over time. Common mistake: Students assume the Fed targets 2% CPI inflation. The Fed's formal target is 2% PCE inflation, which is methodologically different from CPI and typically runs 20-30 basis points lower.",
