    group: "Inflation",
    term: "Cost-push inflation",
    brief: "Inflation caused by rising production costs, which reduce aggregate supply and push prices up while simultaneously reducing output.",
    more: "Oil price spikes, rising wages above productivity growth, supply chain disruptions, and import price increases through currency depreciation all create cost-push inflation. Unlike demand-pull inflation, cost-push produces stagflation: higher prices and lower output at the same time. The policy response is constrained because tightening to reduce inflation deepens the output fall.",
    detailed: "Cost-push inflation was the dominant macroeconomic problem of the 1970s, when successive oil shocks shifted SRAS leftward, producing stagflation that conventional demand management could not resolve. The Fed's response under Volcker in 1979-82 was to tighten aggressively, accepting a deep recession to break inflationary expectations. The 2021-22 inflation episode combined cost-push elements (supply-chain disruptions, energy prices) with demand-pull elements (pandemic fiscal transfers), making it harder to characterize and respond to. Common mistake: Students apply demand-side remedies to cost-push inflation. Raising interest rates or cutting government spending reduces demand but does not address the underlying supply-side cost increase; it worsens the output loss without necessarily resolving the price pressure.",
