    more: "Demand-pull inflation occurs when the economy is operating near or at potential output: further demand stimulus generates price increases rather than real output gains. It is associated with booms, fiscal expansions, and credit-fueled spending. The appropriate policy response is contractionary: tighter monetary or fiscal policy reduces demand toward potential output.",
    detailed: "Demand-pull inflation is the classic Keynesian concern about expansionary policy applied when the economy is already at capacity. The 2021-22 US inflation episode is interpreted by many economists as partly demand-pull: pandemic fiscal transfers substantially boosted household spending at a time when supply remained constrained. Distinguishing demand-pull from cost-push inflation in real time is difficult because both can produce the same headline CPI figure. Common mistake: Students apply demand-pull remedies to cost-push inflation. If inflation is driven by supply constraints rather than excess demand, tightening policy reduces output without addressing the underlying cost pressure.",
