    brief: "A reduction in the rate of inflation, where prices are still rising but at a slower pace than before.",
    more: "Disinflation is distinct from deflation: the price level continues to increase during disinflation, just more slowly. The Volcker disinflation of 1979-83 reduced US CPI from above 14% to below 4% through aggressive interest rate increases, at the cost of a severe recession. Successful disinflation typically requires a credible and sustained commitment from the central bank.",
    detailed: "The cost of disinflation in terms of lost output and employment depends on the sacrifice ratio: the cumulative output loss required to reduce inflation by one percentage point. If inflation expectations are well-anchored, the Fed can achieve disinflation with a smaller sacrifice because wage and price setters quickly update expectations downward. If expectations are entrenched, a larger recession is required to break the wage-price spiral. The 2022-23 Fed tightening cycle achieved significant disinflation with lower output costs than many models predicted, possibly reflecting the anchoring role of the Fed's inflation-targeting credibility. Common mistake: Students confuse disinflation with deflation. During disinflation, prices are still rising; during deflation, the price level is falling.",
