    more: "Goods inflation is typically more volatile than services inflation because it responds more directly to commodity prices, global supply chains, and trade. During the 2021-22 inflation surge, goods inflation led the overall rise due to supply-chain disruptions and post-pandemic demand shifts; it subsequently fell sharply before services inflation remained elevated.",
    detailed: "The goods/services distinction matters for monetary policy because their inflation drivers differ. Goods prices are set in competitive global markets and respond to exchange rates and commodity costs; services prices are more driven by domestic labor costs and are stickier. A goods-led inflation surge may be more transitory than a services-led one because global supply chains tend to normalize. However, if goods inflation feeds into wage demands, it can become embedded in services inflation through second-round effects. Common mistake: Students treat all components of CPI inflation as equally persistent. Goods inflation tends to be more volatile and mean-reverting; services inflation is stickier and more indicative of underlying domestic price pressures.",
