    detailed: "The persistence of services inflation in 2023-24 despite goods disinflation reflected tight US labor markets and sustained rent inflation in official measures. 'Supercore' inflation, which strips out housing from core services, became a closely watched indicator because it captures the wage-driven component of inflation most directly linked to the labor market. Fed officials cited supercore as evidence that underlying domestic price pressures remained elevated even as headline inflation fell. Common mistake: Students assume that because goods inflation fell sharply, overall inflation was under control. Services inflation can remain elevated long after goods prices normalize, keeping headline inflation above the Fed's target.",
