    brief: "A breakdown in the network of suppliers, producers, and logistics providers that results in shortages, delivery delays, and cost increases across multiple industries.",
    more: "Supply chain disruptions act as a negative supply-side shock: they raise production costs and reduce output simultaneously. The COVID-19 pandemic triggered the largest global supply chain disruption in decades, contributing to the 2021-22 inflation surge through a combination of reduced manufacturing capacity and surging post-pandemic demand for goods.",
    detailed: "The 2021-22 supply chain crisis revealed how concentrated and vulnerable global production had become to single points of failure. Just-in-time inventory systems, offshoring of manufacturing, and tight shipping schedules meant there was no buffer when pandemic lockdowns disrupted production in Asia and port congestion backed up logistics networks. The disruptions were self-reinforcing: shortages prompted precautionary stockpiling, which worsened shortages further. This episode accelerated political interest in reshoring and supply chain diversification. Common mistake: Students treat supply chain disruptions as exclusively a supply phenomenon. Demand surges, such as stimulus-fueled goods demand during the pandemic, can overwhelm supply chains that would otherwise be adequate, making the disruption partly a demand-driven outcome.",
