    detailed: "The classic wage-price spiral of the 1970s was driven by powerful unions, oil shocks, and accommodative monetary policy that validated each round of wage and price increases. The Volcker tightening broke the spiral by demonstrating that the Fed would accept high unemployment to restore price stability, anchoring inflation expectations permanently. Modern labor markets, with weaker unions and more flexible employment, make a full wage-price spiral less likely but not impossible. The 2021-22 inflation episode raised concerns about spiral dynamics; the evidence suggests that while wages rose substantially, a fully self-reinforcing spiral did not materialize. Common mistake: Students assume any period of rising wages and rising prices constitutes a wage-price spiral. A spiral requires wages and prices to accelerate each other persistently; one-off wage adjustments to a price shock are not a spiral.",
