    detailed: "Absolute advantage compares productivity levels directly: if the US produces 10 units of a good per worker while Brazil produces 8, the US has an absolute advantage. Adam Smith originally argued countries should specialize where they have absolute advantage, but Ricardo showed this was incomplete. A country can hold absolute advantage in all goods yet still gain from trade by specializing where its comparative advantage lies. Absolute advantage matters for living standards, as more productive economies are wealthier, but comparative advantage determines the direction of trade. Common mistake: Students assume a country with absolute advantage in everything should produce everything, ignoring the opportunity cost gains from specialization.",
