    more: "Under a floating exchange rate, appreciation results from increased demand for the currency, often driven by higher interest rates, stronger economic performance, or improved trade balance. Appreciation makes exports more expensive in foreign markets and imports cheaper domestically, tending to reduce net exports and aggregate demand.",
    detailed: "Currency appreciation creates winners and losers within the domestic economy. Importers benefit from lower costs; exporters face reduced competitiveness. Consumers benefit from cheaper imported goods; workers in export industries face job pressure. The overall effect on output depends on the relative magnitudes of these effects and the price elasticities of demand for exports and imports. Strong appreciation can undermine manufacturing, contributing to deindustrialization. Common mistake: Students assume appreciation always strengthens the economy. While it lowers import prices and reduces inflation, appreciation typically reduces net exports and aggregate demand, creating a growth trade-off.",
