    detailed: "The DXY is heavily weighted toward the euro (approximately 57.6%), which means it is more a measure of dollar/euro dynamics than a comprehensive global trade-weighted index. More complete dollar strength measures, such as the Fed's own trade-weighted dollar index, include currencies of all major trading partners. A strong DXY reduces inflation from imported goods but tightens financial conditions globally, as dollar-denominated debt becomes more expensive to service for foreign borrowers. Common mistake: Students assume a high DXY always benefits the US economy. Dollar strength reduces import prices (lowering inflation) but also weakens export competitiveness and tightens financial conditions for emerging market economies that hold dollar debt, which can feed back into global demand.",
