    more: "M2 is the primary broad money aggregate tracked by the Federal Reserve, comprising currency in circulation, checking accounts, savings accounts, and small time deposits. M2 growth is watched as a potential leading indicator of inflation, though its predictive power has weakened as financial innovation has changed how money is held.",
    detailed: "The relationship between broad money growth and inflation is captured by the quantity theory of money (MV = PQ), but in practice the velocity of money (V) is unstable, making the link between M2 and inflation unreliable in the short run. Post-2008, M2 grew rapidly as the Fed expanded its balance sheet, but inflation remained subdued for over a decade because velocity fell sharply as banks accumulated excess reserves. When M2 surged again in 2020-21 and velocity stabilized, inflation followed. Common mistake: Students assume rapid broad money growth always causes inflation immediately. Velocity is the missing link; if additional money is hoarded rather than spent, the price level need not rise.",
