    detailed: "Capital markets differ from money markets in the term of instruments traded and the risk involved. In capital markets, long-term interest rates are determined by current short-term rates and expectations of future short-term rates plus a term premium. Quantitative easing operates primarily through capital markets: by buying long-term Treasuries and mortgage-backed securities, the Fed reduces long-term yields, stimulating investment and housing activity. Common mistake: Students use 'capital market' loosely to mean any financial market. Capital markets specifically deal in long-term instruments; money markets deal in short-term liquid instruments.",
