    more: "Credit expansion stimulates aggregate demand by allowing households to consume and firms to invest beyond their immediate cash flows. Excessive credit growth relative to productive capacity creates asset price bubbles and systemic risk. The availability and cost of credit is a key channel through which monetary policy influences the real economy.",
    detailed: "Credit cycles amplify business cycles through the financial accelerator: rising asset prices increase collateral values, enabling more borrowing, which pushes asset prices higher. When the cycle turns, falling asset values reduce collateral, forcing deleveraging, which pushes asset prices lower. This dynamic was central to the 2007-09 financial crisis. Hyman Minsky's framework describes how long periods of financial stability breed the risk-taking that makes the system fragile. Common mistake: Students treat credit as simply borrowing from existing savings. In a fractional reserve banking system, credit creation expands the money supply beyond existing deposits; credit is not a zero-sum redistribution of existing resources.",
