    more: "Borrowing from the discount window is available to eligible depository institutions facing temporary liquidity needs. The primary credit rate (the main discount window rate) is typically set above the federal funds rate target, making it a backstop rather than a routine funding source. In a crisis, the Fed lowers the discount rate and broadens access to prevent bank runs.",
    detailed: "The discount rate signals the Fed's stance on banking system liquidity and willingness to act as lender of last resort. During the 2008 financial crisis, the Fed lowered the discount rate, extended the term of lending, and established emergency lending facilities to prevent system-wide liquidity failure. The stigma attached to discount window borrowing, which markets interpret as a sign of weakness, limits its use in normal times. Common mistake: Students confuse the discount rate with the federal funds rate. The federal funds rate governs interbank overnight lending and is the primary policy tool; the discount rate governs central bank lending to banks and serves as a backstop facility.",
