    term: "Excess reserves",
    brief: "Reserves held by commercial banks above the minimum required by regulation, deposited at the Federal Reserve.",
    more: "Before 2008, US banks held minimal excess reserves because idle reserves earned no return. After 2008, the Fed began paying interest on excess reserves (IOER), incentivizing banks to hold large quantities rather than lending them out. Excess reserves reached $2.7 trillion by 2014, fundamentally changing the monetary policy transmission mechanism.",
    detailed: "The existence of large excess reserves broke the textbook money multiplier model. In the standard model, base money expands through lending until reserves equal the required minimum. When banks hold excess reserves voluntarily, the multiplier is indeterminate and base money expansion need not translate into credit expansion or inflation. This explains why quantitative easing, which created vast quantities of excess reserves, did not produce the inflation many predicted. The interest rate on excess reserves (now IORB) has become a key tool for controlling the federal funds rate. Common mistake: Students apply the textbook money multiplier to an economy with large excess reserves. The multiplier assumes banks lend all excess reserves; when excess reserve holding is voluntary and interest-bearing, this assumption fails.",
