    detailed: "The federal funds rate is the operational target through which the FOMC's rate decisions are implemented. Since 2008, the fed funds market has shrunk relative to its pre-crisis size because banks hold large excess reserves and no longer need to borrow frequently to meet requirements. The corridor system using IORB and the ON RRP rate replaced the traditional fed funds market as the primary mechanism for rate control. The effective federal funds rate (EFFR) is published daily by the New York Fed. Common mistake: Students assume the fed funds rate is a single number set directly by the Fed. The FOMC sets a target range; the actual rate is market-determined and steered into the range using administered rates paid on reserves.",
