    detailed: "Financial markets are integral to monetary policy transmission. When the Fed cuts rates, equity and bond markets reprice almost instantly, affecting household wealth and corporate borrowing costs before any real-sector adjustment occurs. Market efficiency theory holds that asset prices reflect all available information, but behavioral finance demonstrates systematic departures from rational pricing. Financial crises often begin with mispricing in financial markets that eventually forces abrupt corrections with real-economy consequences. Common mistake: Students treat financial market activity as equivalent to economic activity. Financial markets can boom while the real economy stagnates (the 2010-14 equity rally during a weak labor market recovery); market prices signal expectations, not current economic conditions.",
