    more: "The FOMC comprises the seven members of the Federal Reserve Board of Governors and five of the twelve Federal Reserve Bank presidents (New York always votes; the others rotate). It meets eight times per year and releases a statement, updated projections (the 'dot plot'), and a press conference after each meeting.",
    detailed: "The FOMC operates by consensus, with the Federal Reserve Chair playing a dominant role in shaping the committee's direction. The 'dot plot' of each member's rate projections has become a major market-moving communication tool, influencing long-term rates through forward guidance even before any policy action is taken. FOMC decisions are global events: changes in the federal funds rate target affect dollar borrowing costs and exchange rates worldwide. Common mistake: Students assume all 12 Federal Reserve Bank presidents vote at every FOMC meeting. Only the New York Fed president votes permanently; the other eleven rotate on an annual basis, so the voting composition changes each year.",
