    group: "Money & Monetary Policy",
    term: "Forward guidance",
    brief: "Central bank communication about the likely future path of monetary policy, used to shape expectations and influence long-term interest rates without changing the current policy rate.",
    more: "By credibly committing to keep rates low for an extended period, the Fed can push down long-term rates even after exhausting conventional rate cuts. The Fed used forward guidance extensively after 2008 and 2020, conditioning future rate increases on achieving specific employment and inflation thresholds.",
    detailed: "Forward guidance works through the expectations hypothesis of the term structure: long-term rates equal the average of expected future short-term rates. If the Fed credibly commits to a low rate path, long-term rates fall, easing financial conditions. The challenge is credibility: if markets doubt the commitment, the guidance has no effect. Outcome-based guidance (rates stay low until unemployment falls below X%) is more credible than calendar-based guidance (rates stay low until 2025) because it adjusts automatically to economic developments. Common mistake: Students treat forward guidance as equivalent to actually cutting rates. Guidance influences long-term rates through expectations; its effectiveness depends entirely on the central bank's credibility and the market's belief that the guidance will be honored.",
