    more: "When a bank receives a $1,000 deposit and holds 10% ($100) as reserves, it can lend $900. The borrower's deposit of $900 enables further lending, generating a multiple expansion of deposits through successive rounds. This process is described by the money multiplier.",
    detailed: "Fractional reserve banking makes banks inherently vulnerable to runs: if all depositors demanded their money simultaneously, the bank could not pay because most funds are tied up in illiquid loans. Deposit insurance (FDIC in the US, up to $250,000) and lender of last resort facilities from the Fed were created precisely to prevent this dynamic. The actual money creation process in modern banking is more complex than the textbook deposit multiplier: banks create deposits when they make loans, and reserve requirements no longer bind US banks following their removal in March 2020. Common mistake: Students describe banks as intermediaries that lend out existing deposits. Fractional reserve banking means banks create new deposits by lending; money creation is endogenous to lending decisions, not limited to pre-existing savings.",
