    brief: "The cost of borrowing money or the return on lending, expressed as a percentage of the principal per year.",
    more: "Interest rates vary by term, credit risk, and liquidity. The federal funds rate anchors short-term rates; long-term rates reflect expectations of future short-term rates plus a term premium. Real interest rates adjust for inflation: if the nominal rate is 5% and inflation is 3%, the real rate is approximately 2%.",
    detailed: "The distinction between real and nominal interest rates is critical for economic decision-making. Investment decisions should be made on the basis of real rates, because borrowing costs and returns both need to be measured in purchasing power terms. In periods of unexpectedly high inflation, borrowers benefit because they repay in depreciated dollars; lenders lose. The Fisher equation (nominal rate = real rate + expected inflation) describes this relationship. Common mistake: Students use nominal interest rates to assess the burden of borrowing. The relevant rate for household and firm decisions is the real interest rate; a 10% nominal rate with 8% inflation is less burdensome than a 3% nominal rate with 0% inflation.",
