    more: "Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan, and Morgan Stanley are the leading US investment banks. They underwrite new share and bond issues, facilitating capital market access for issuers. Investment banks do not take retail deposits; they fund themselves through wholesale markets and their own capital, making them more sensitive to financial market conditions.",
    detailed: "The separation of commercial and investment banking, mandated by the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933 and repealed in 1999, was reinstated in limited form by the Volcker Rule under the 2010 Dodd-Frank Act, which restricts proprietary trading by deposit-taking institutions. Investment banks' use of leverage amplifies their returns in good times and losses in bad times; Lehman Brothers' collapse in 2008 triggered the global financial crisis because of its role in interconnected wholesale funding markets. Common mistake: Students treat investment banks as similar to commercial banks. Investment banks do not create money through deposit-taking and lending; they facilitate capital market transactions and are funded through market instruments rather than insured deposits.",
