    more: "Liquidity is distinct from solvency: a firm can be solvent (assets exceed liabilities) but illiquid (unable to meet immediate cash demands). Banks are required to hold sufficient liquid assets (the Liquidity Coverage Ratio under Basel III) to survive a 30-day stress scenario. Treasury bills are the benchmark liquid asset.",
    detailed: "The liquidity spectrum runs from most liquid (cash) to least liquid (real estate, private equity). During financial crises, liquidity dries up even for assets normally considered liquid: the interbank market froze in 2008 and commercial paper markets seized. The Fed's lender of last resort function exists to inject liquidity into the system when private liquidity provision fails, preventing solvent banks from failing due to short-term funding shortfalls. Common mistake: Students conflate liquidity with value. An asset can be highly valuable but illiquid (a property, a stake in a private company); conversely, a low-value asset can be highly liquid. The distinction matters for financial stability analysis.",
