    more: "Conventional monetary policy operates through the federal funds rate. Expansionary policy (rate cuts) stimulates aggregate demand; contractionary policy (rate hikes) reduces it. Unconventional tools include quantitative easing, forward guidance, and lending facilities for financial markets.",
    detailed: "Monetary policy acts with long and variable lags (Milton Friedman's phrase): the full effect of a rate change takes 12-24 months to work through the economy. This means policy must be forward-looking, responding to expected future conditions rather than current data. The Fed's 2020 shift to average inflation targeting, under which it would allow inflation to run above 2% to compensate for below-target periods, reflects lessons learned from the post-2008 period of undershooting. Common mistake: Students assume monetary policy has immediate and precise effects. The transmission mechanism involves multiple channels, each with different lags; the aggregate effect of a given rate change on inflation and output is highly uncertain and model-dependent.",
