    brief: "The channels through which changes in the federal funds rate and other Fed actions affect output, employment, and inflation in the broader economy.",
    more: "Key channels include: the interest rate channel (lower rates reduce borrowing costs), the asset price channel (lower rates raise equity and property prices, boosting wealth and collateral), the exchange rate channel (lower rates weaken the dollar, improving competitiveness), and the credit channel (lower rates ease bank lending conditions).",
    detailed: "The transmission mechanism is powerful in theory but uncertain in practice. Different channels dominate at different stages of the cycle. During financial crises, the credit channel may seize up even as the interest rate channel is active, limiting the Fed's ability to stimulate. The wealth effect from asset price appreciation is most powerful for high-income households with large financial portfolios, which is why monetary policy easing in 2009-15 raised asset prices substantially while having modest effects on household consumption. Common mistake: Students reduce monetary policy transmission to the interest rate channel alone. The asset price, exchange rate, and credit channels are all quantitatively significant; ignoring them gives an incomplete picture of how monetary policy affects the real economy.",
