    detailed: "This entry exists to ensure compatibility with references in related terms. For full detail on FOMC structure and decision-making, see the dedicated FOMC entry. The FOMC is the US equivalent of the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee; both are independent committees setting short-term policy rates within a mandate set by their respective legislatures. Common mistake: Students assume the Federal Reserve Chair alone sets interest rates. The FOMC votes on rate decisions; the Chair has significant influence but must build consensus among committee members.",
