    detailed: "The 2008 financial crisis intensified the too-big-to-fail moral hazard debate. The US government's rescue of Bear Stearns and AIG, followed by the decision not to rescue Lehman Brothers, demonstrated the inconsistency of bailout policy. The Dodd-Frank Act's Orderly Liquidation Authority sought to resolve systemically important institutions without taxpayer bailouts, but the credibility of this commitment remains questioned by market participants who still price in implicit guarantees. Common mistake: Students describe moral hazard as dishonest behavior. It is a rational response to incentives: if risks are socialized while gains are private, rational actors will take more risk. The problem lies in the incentive structure, not individual ethics.",
