    detailed: "The Taylor rule is a descriptive benchmark, not a mechanical formula the Fed is bound to follow. It captures the intuition that policy should lean against both high inflation and weak output. Significant policy debates concern the appropriate value of the rule's coefficients and how to measure the neutral rate and the output gap, all of which are unobservable. The rule suggested the Fed kept rates too low for too long in the 2000s (contributing to the housing bubble) and possibly after 2020. Common mistake: Students assume the Fed mechanically follows the Taylor rule. It is a benchmark and communication tool; the FOMC exercises judgment that incorporates factors not captured in the simple formula, including financial stability and risk management considerations.",
