    detailed: "Economic cycles are driven by demand-side shocks (financial crises, oil price spikes, policy errors) and the internal dynamics of investment and credit. The accelerator-multiplier interaction amplifies initial shocks into extended expansions and contractions. Modern stabilization policy through the Federal Reserve and fiscal automatic stabilizers aims to moderate the cycle without eliminating it. Common mistake: Students assume economic cycles are regular and predictable. The NBER has documented US cycles since 1854 showing substantial variation in duration and amplitude; cycles are recurrent but not periodic.",
