    brief: "The total value of all final goods and services produced in a country, measured at current market prices without adjusting for inflation.",
    more: "Nominal GDP rises when real output increases or when the price level rises. To compare economic output across years meaningfully, economists use real GDP, which strips out the price effect. Nominal GDP growth is relevant for assessing debt sustainability: if nominal GDP grows faster than the interest rate on debt, the debt-to-GDP ratio falls.",
    detailed: "Nominal GDP targeting has been proposed as an alternative monetary policy framework to inflation targeting. Under nominal GDP targeting, the central bank would aim for a stable growth rate in the dollar value of output, automatically easing when output falls and tightening when it rises, regardless of whether the movement is driven by prices or real activity. Proponents argue this framework is more robust to supply shocks than strict inflation targeting. Common mistake: Students use nominal GDP to compare living standards across time periods. A doubling of nominal GDP over 20 years with 50% inflation represents a much smaller real gain than a doubling with 5% inflation; real GDP is the appropriate comparator.",
    seeAlso: ["real-gdp", "gdp-gross-domestic-product", "inflation", "price-level", "national-income"],
