    term: "Productive capacity",
    brief: "The maximum level of output an economy can sustain using its available resources at full employment without generating accelerating inflation.",
    more: "Productive capacity is equivalent to potential GDP and is represented by the position of the LRAS curve. It is determined by the quantity and quality of labor, capital, natural resources, and technology. Supply-side policies aim to increase productive capacity by improving the efficiency and quantity of these factors.",
    detailed: "Productive capacity is a long-run concept that changes slowly with investment, demographics, and technology. In the short run, actual output can exceed productive capacity temporarily (positive output gap), but only at the cost of accelerating inflation. Hysteresis effects can reduce productive capacity during prolonged recessions, making demand management in deep downturns a supply-side concern as well as a demand-side one. Common mistake: Students treat productive capacity as a fixed ceiling. Investment, education, and technological change continuously shift it; supply-side policies explicitly aim to raise it.",
