    group: "National Income & Growth",
    term: "Productivity",
    brief: "Output per unit of input, typically measured as labor productivity (output per worker or per hour) or total factor productivity (output per unit of all inputs combined).",
    more: "Productivity growth is the primary source of long-run improvements in living standards: higher output per worker means higher real wages are sustainable without generating inflation. The US experienced a productivity surge in the late 1990s driven by IT investment; the post-2008 productivity slowdown across advanced economies remains partially unexplained.",
    detailed: "The post-2008 productivity slowdown is one of the most important puzzles in macroeconomics. Explanations include mismeasurement (digital services are poorly captured in GDP statistics), misallocation of resources to zombie firms kept alive by low interest rates, reduced business dynamism, and a genuine decline in the pace of technological diffusion. The potential for AI-driven productivity acceleration is significant but uncertain. Common mistake: Students conflate productivity with output. An economy can have more workers producing more output without any productivity improvement; productivity specifically measures how much output is generated per unit of input.",
