    curricula: ['ap-economics'],
    group: "National Income & Growth",
    term: "Purchasing power parity (PPP)",
    brief: "An exchange rate adjustment that equalizes the purchasing power of different currencies by accounting for differences in the price of a comparable basket of goods across countries.",
    more: "GDP adjusted for PPP allows meaningful cross-country comparisons of living standards. A dollar buys more in a low-income country than in the US because non-traded goods are cheaper there; PPP correction accounts for this. China's economy is larger than the US by PPP-adjusted GDP but smaller at market exchange rates.",
    detailed: "PPP is theoretically expected to hold in the long run as arbitrage in traded goods equalizes prices internationally. In practice, non-traded services do not equalize, and the Balassa-Samuelson effect predicts that richer countries have higher price levels for non-traded goods. PPP estimates are sensitive to the choice of base year and the goods included in the comparison basket. Common mistake: Students use market exchange rates for international welfare comparisons. Market exchange rates reflect capital flows and financial conditions; PPP rates better capture real differences in living standards, particularly between high and low income countries.",
