    term: "Real GDP",
    brief: "GDP adjusted for changes in the price level, measuring the actual volume of goods and services produced rather than their dollar value.",
    more: "Real GDP uses chain-weighted prices to strip out inflation, allowing genuine comparisons of economic output over time. The Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA) publishes US real GDP quarterly. Real GDP growth above the long-run trend implies the economy is expanding faster than its sustainable pace.",
    detailed: "Chain-weighting, adopted by the US in 1996, continuously updates the price weights used to calculate real GDP, avoiding distortions that arise when a fixed base year becomes outdated. This matters when rapidly changing sectors (technology goods, for example) experience large relative price shifts. Real GDP is the appropriate variable for assessing economic growth and business cycle analysis, but even real GDP growth can mask distributional changes. Common mistake: Students assume real GDP growth directly measures welfare improvement. Real GDP measures output volume; distribution, quality of public services, environmental sustainability, and leisure time all affect welfare independently of real GDP.",
