    more: "Real GDP per capita is the standard measure for comparing living standards across countries and tracking improvements over time. The US has among the highest real GDP per capita of large economies. Growth in real GDP per capita requires output to grow faster than population.",
    detailed: "Real GDP per capita is an average that conceals distributional variation. A country can have high GDP per capita with most of the population below median income if wealth is highly concentrated. Alternative measures such as median household income, the Gini coefficient, and the Human Development Index provide additional dimensions of wellbeing beyond the average output measure. Common mistake: Students treat real GDP per capita as equivalent to the average person's income. Per capita GDP is total output divided by population; the actual income of a typical household depends critically on distribution, which per capita GDP does not capture.",
