    term: "Recession",
    brief: "A significant decline in economic activity defined by the NBER as a period of broadly based contraction lasting more than a few months, visible in GDP, employment, income, and industrial production.",
    more: "The popular rule of two consecutive quarters of negative real GDP growth is a rough approximation; the NBER's official definition is broader and considers the depth, diffusion, and duration of the contraction. Recessions are associated with rising unemployment, falling business investment, and reduced tax revenues.",
    detailed: "Recessions vary enormously in severity. The 2008-09 recession was the deepest since the Great Depression, with GDP falling 4.3% peak to trough and unemployment reaching 10%. The 2020 recession was the sharpest ever recorded but also the shortest. Policy response has become faster and larger over time, reflecting lessons from the Depression and the 2008 crisis. Common mistake: Students apply the two-quarters-of-negative-growth rule as the official US definition. The NBER Business Cycle Dating Committee is the official arbiter; it uses a broader and more flexible framework than the two-quarter rule.",
