    group: "National Income & Growth",
    term: "Spare capacity",
    brief: "Unused productive resources in an economy, including unemployed workers and underutilized capital, indicating output below potential.",
    more: "Spare capacity corresponds to a negative output gap. Its presence implies expansionary policy can raise output without generating significant inflation, because additional demand is met by previously idle resources. Measures include the unemployment rate relative to NAIRU, industrial capacity utilization, and the prime-age labor force participation rate.",
    detailed: "Spare capacity is not costless merely because resources are idle. Long-term unemployment erodes skills; unused capital depreciates; infrastructure falls into disrepair. The costs of sustained spare capacity accumulate over time and partly justify activist stabilization policy. The Fed's 2020 shift to flexible average inflation targeting was partly motivated by evidence that running the economy tighter than previously thought cleared spare capacity without triggering inflation. Common mistake: Students assume spare capacity eliminates all inflation risk. If spare capacity is concentrated in sectors that do not produce goods in high demand, it cannot be activated to meet that demand; bottlenecks can generate inflation even with aggregate spare capacity.",
