    more: "Material living standards are approximated by real GDP per capita and real disposable income. Non-material factors include life expectancy, access to healthcare and education, safety, and political freedom. The Human Development Index (HDI) combines income, health, and education into a composite measure.",
    detailed: "Rising real GDP per capita does not guarantee rising living standards for most households if gains are concentrated at the top. Median household income in the US grew significantly more slowly than per capita GDP between 1980 and 2020, reflecting rising inequality. Environmental degradation from economic activity can reduce quality of life even as measured GDP rises. These limitations have driven interest in beyond-GDP measures of national wellbeing. Common mistake: Students equate rising GDP with improving living standards. GDP measures output, not distribution or sustainability; living standards depend critically on how output is divided and what environmental costs it imposes.",
