    more: "Supply-side improvements shift the LRAS curve rightward, raising potential output without generating inflation. They include increases in labor force participation, investment in physical and human capital, technological innovation, deregulation that improves resource allocation, and trade opening that deepens specialization.",
    detailed: "The distinction between supply-side improvements and supply-side policies matters. Improvements refer to the actual shift in productive capacity; policies are the government actions intended to bring them about. Not all supply-side policies achieve improvements: poorly designed deregulation can reduce output, and education spending that does not improve skills is not a supply-side improvement. Evaluation requires empirical assessment of outcomes, not just policy intent. Common mistake: Students assume any supply-side policy automatically produces supply-side improvements. Outcomes depend on policy design, implementation, and whether they address genuine market failures or simply redistribute rents.",
