    brief: "Government policies intended to increase the economy's productive capacity by improving incentives, increasing competition, enhancing human capital, or expanding the labor supply.",
    more: "Market-based supply-side policies include tax rate reductions, deregulation, privatization, and trade liberalization. Interventionist supply-side policies include investment in education and infrastructure, research subsidies, and active labor market programs. Both types aim to shift LRAS rightward rather than stimulate short-run aggregate demand.",
    detailed: "Supply-side economics gained prominence in the 1980s under the Reagan administration, which combined income tax cuts with deregulation. The empirical record is mixed: the 1986 Tax Reform Act broadened the base and lowered rates with positive efficiency effects; the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act generated a significant structural deficit without the promised sustained growth surge. Interventionist supply-side policies such as the Inflation Reduction Act's clean energy incentives combine demand and supply objectives. Common mistake: Students conflate supply-side policies exclusively with tax cuts. A wide range of interventions, from education spending to infrastructure investment to regulatory reform, can shift the LRAS curve rightward if well-designed.",
    seeAlso: ["supply-side-improvements", "long-run-economic-growth", "productive-capacity", "fiscal-policy", "human-capital"],
