    detailed: "UI claims measure a specific administrative population, not total unemployment. Workers who have exhausted benefits, those who never qualified (self-employed, gig workers), and those who have stopped searching are not counted. During COVID-19, claims reached a historic 6.9 million in April 2020. The data are volatile week to week due to seasonal patterns, requiring four-week moving averages for trend analysis. Common mistake: Students assume UI claims data captures total unemployment. UI claims measure only insured unemployment; a full picture requires reading claims alongside the BLS unemployment rate, payrolls, and participation rate.",
