    more: "Cyclical unemployment rises in recessions as falling output causes firms to reduce labor demand, and falls in expansions as rising demand increases hiring. Unlike frictional or structural unemployment, it can be reduced by expansionary monetary or fiscal policy that boosts aggregate demand.",
    detailed: "Cyclical unemployment is the form of unemployment that Keynesian economics specifically addresses: if it is caused by demand deficiency, demand stimulus is the appropriate remedy. The debate over how much unemployment after 2008 was cyclical versus structural had significant policy implications. If unemployment was cyclical, stimulus was appropriate; if structural, stimulus would generate inflation without reducing unemployment. Evidence suggests it was mostly cyclical in 2009-13, making the case for fiscal stimulus strong. Common mistake: Students assume all unemployment responds to expansionary policy. Only cyclical unemployment responds to demand stimulus; structural and frictional unemployment require supply-side interventions such as retraining and mobility support.",
