    more: "The economically inactive include retirees, students, caregivers, and discouraged workers who have given up searching for jobs. The labor force participation rate measures the share of the working-age population that is employed or actively seeking work; a falling participation rate can mask labor market weakness in the official unemployment rate.",
    detailed: "Post-pandemic US labor force participation remains below pre-2020 levels, partly reflecting early retirements and long COVID health effects. The prime-age (25-54) participation rate is more analytically useful than the overall rate because it is less affected by demographic aging. Economists debate how much post-pandemic inactivity is reversible versus permanent. Common mistake: Students assume the unemployment rate fully captures labor market slack. Economic inactivity, underemployment, and discouraged workers represent additional slack not captured in the headline U-3 rate.",
