    detailed: "The two BLS employment surveys often diverge in the short run. The payroll survey is larger and more precise for month-to-month changes but misses the self-employed and new businesses. The household survey captures self-employment and multiple job holding. Employment quality, measured by hours worked, real wages, and benefits coverage, matters as much as employment quantity for assessing labor market health. Common mistake: Students treat employment and unemployment as mirror images. Employment and unemployment can both rise simultaneously if the labor force is growing; the participation rate must be tracked alongside both measures.",
