    more: "Frictional unemployment is present even in a healthy economy: workers who voluntarily quit, new graduates searching for their first job, and those moving between regions all contribute to it. It reflects information imperfections and the time required to match workers with appropriate vacancies.",
    detailed: "Frictional unemployment is considered unavoidable and even desirable: it reflects workers searching for better matches rather than accepting the first available job, which improves long-run productivity and allocative efficiency. Generous unemployment insurance extends frictional unemployment by reducing urgency to accept lower-quality offers. Active labor market programs that improve job matching reduce frictional unemployment. Common mistake: Students describe frictional unemployment as a sign of labor market failure. It is a natural feature of dynamic labor markets; zero frictional unemployment would indicate a market with no job transitions, which would be highly inefficient.",
