    more: "Involuntary unemployment can be cyclical (caused by deficient aggregate demand) or structural (caused by skills or location mismatches). It is distinct from voluntary unemployment, where workers choose not to accept available jobs at market wages. Its presence implies the labor market is not clearing.",
    detailed: "The Keynesian theory of involuntary unemployment challenged the classical view that labor markets clear automatically. If wages are sticky downward, a fall in aggregate demand does not reduce wages enough to restore full employment; instead it causes involuntary unemployment that persists until demand recovers. The size of involuntary unemployment determines how much slack the economy has and whether expansionary policy will increase output rather than wages. Common mistake: Students assume all unemployment is voluntary or reflects worker preferences. Involuntary unemployment specifically refers to workers unable to find work at prevailing wages, not those unwilling to work at lower wages.",
