    more: "The CPS surveys approximately 60,000 households monthly, classifying respondents as employed, unemployed (without work but actively searching), or economically inactive. The U-3 unemployment rate is the headline measure. The BLS also publishes U-6, which adds discouraged workers and involuntary part-timers.",
    detailed: "The CPS headline rate (U-3) counts as unemployed only those without work who actively searched in the past four weeks and are available to work. This excludes marginally attached workers and discouraged workers. U-6, the broadest measure, includes all these groups plus part-time workers who would prefer full-time employment. In weak labor markets, U-3 can significantly understate true labor market slack. Common mistake: Students treat U-3 as the only relevant unemployment measure. U-6, participation rates, prime-age employment ratios, and wage growth all contribute to a fuller picture of labor market conditions.",
