    more: "In competitive labor markets, wages adjust to clear the market. In practice, minimum wages, search frictions, and efficiency wage considerations prevent wages from behaving like standard competitive prices. The Federal Reserve monitors labor market conditions closely because tight markets generate wage-push inflation.",
    detailed: "The labor market is segmented by skill, geography, and industry, meaning conditions vary sharply across segments. Monopsony power, where a dominant employer faces little competition for workers, allows wages to be set below the competitive level, providing an economic justification for minimum wages. The post-pandemic US labor market featured unusual tightness (a Beveridge curve shift) that complicated the Fed's inflation-fighting task. Common mistake: Students treat labor supply as simply the number of available workers. Labor supply also involves hours worked, effort, and the decision to enter the labor force, all of which respond to wages, benefit programs, and non-work alternatives.",
