    term: "NAIRU",
    brief: "The Non-Accelerating Inflation Rate of Unemployment: the unemployment rate consistent with stable inflation, below which tighter labor markets generate accelerating wage-price pressure.",
    more: "When unemployment falls below the NAIRU, firms compete for workers and wages rise faster than productivity, generating cost-push inflation. The NAIRU is not fixed; structural changes in the labor market and technology shift it over time. The Fed monitors unemployment relative to estimated NAIRU to assess inflation risk.",
    detailed: "NAIRU is unobservable and its estimates have been repeatedly revised. After 2015, US unemployment fell well below conventional NAIRU estimates without generating significant inflation, leading economists to revise estimates downward. The 2019 experience of very low unemployment without inflation acceleration influenced the Fed's adoption of average inflation targeting and its commitment to allow the labor market to run hotter before tightening. Common mistake: Students treat NAIRU as a fixed, known number. It is an estimate that shifts over time and is subject to considerable uncertainty; policy based on a mismeasured NAIRU can tighten or ease at the wrong time.",
