    more: "The natural rate is the equilibrium unemployment rate consistent with stable wages and prices, approximately equivalent to NAIRU. Policies to reduce the natural rate focus on reducing frictional unemployment (better job matching) and structural unemployment (retraining and education) rather than boosting aggregate demand.",
    detailed: "The natural rate concept, introduced by Friedman and Phelps in the late 1960s, challenged the view that policymakers could permanently trade higher inflation for lower unemployment. They argued that any unemployment below the natural rate would be sustained only by accelerating inflation. The natural rate is not immutable: it fell as labor market flexibility increased in the 1990s-2000s and may have fallen further with improved job-matching technology. Common mistake: Students assume the natural rate implies an acceptable level of unemployment that requires no policy response. Structural policies can lower the natural rate; the question is whether cyclical or structural factors are driving unemployment above it.",
