    more: "When real wages exceed the level at which labor demand equals labor supply, unemployment results. Minimum wages, union bargaining power, and efficiency wage considerations can all produce real wages above the market-clearing level. Classical economists argue this is the primary cause of persistent unemployment.",
    detailed: "The real wage unemployment argument underpins classical and supply-side critiques of wage rigidity. If real wages cannot fall to clear the market after a negative shock, unemployment persists. Keynesian economists counter that cutting real wages in a recession would reduce household spending and aggregate demand, potentially worsening unemployment through the multiplier. This debate shapes policy responses: supply-siders favor labor market flexibility; Keynesians favor demand stimulus. Common mistake: Students assume real wage unemployment is always caused by minimum wages. Any mechanism that prevents real wage adjustment, including long-term wage contracts, union agreements, and efficiency wage considerations, can produce the same outcome.",
