    more: "Seasonal unemployment is temporary and predictable: agricultural workers face reduced demand in winter; resort and tourism workers face off-season layoffs; retail and warehouse employment rises before major holidays. Official unemployment statistics are seasonally adjusted to remove these predictable patterns.",
    detailed: "Seasonal adjustment removes the predictable seasonal pattern from the unemployment data so that month-to-month changes reflect genuine economic trends rather than calendar effects. Without seasonal adjustment, December retail hiring would appear as an improvement and January layoffs as a deterioration, masking the underlying trend. Seasonal unemployment is not a policy failure; it reflects efficient allocation of labor across the year in industries with inherently seasonal demand. Common mistake: Students treat seasonal unemployment as a form of structural or cyclical unemployment requiring policy intervention. It is predictable and self-correcting; workers in seasonal industries typically expect and plan for the off-season.",
