    detailed: "The relationship between wage growth and inflation is central to monetary policy. If wage growth consistently exceeds productivity growth plus the inflation target, it is likely to generate sustained inflation. In 2021-23, US wage growth reached its highest levels in decades, partly driven by labor market tightness from stimulus and partly by post-pandemic sectoral reallocation. The Fed raised rates aggressively partly to cool wage growth to a pace consistent with 2% PCE inflation. Common mistake: Students assume any wage growth generates inflation. Wage growth equal to productivity growth plus the inflation target (approximately 2%) is sustainable and does not add to inflationary pressure; only excess wage growth above this level is problematic.",
