    more: "An inflationary gap occurs when aggregate demand is strong enough to push output above the economy's long-run potential. In the AD-AS model it is represented by equilibrium to the right of LRAS. The gap produces rising prices as firms bid up wages and input costs in the face of excess demand.",
    detailed: "The inflationary gap concept maps directly onto the positive output gap: actual GDP exceeds potential GDP, meaning resources are being utilized beyond their sustainable rate. The appropriate policy response is contractionary: the Federal Reserve raises the federal funds rate to cool demand, or fiscal policy tightens through reduced spending or higher taxes. Left unaddressed, an inflationary gap closes through rising wages and prices that shift SRAS leftward until a new long-run equilibrium is restored at potential output with a higher price level. Common mistake: Students assume the economy automatically and quickly closes an inflationary gap. The self-correcting mechanism works through rising wages and input costs, which takes time; in the interim, inflation becomes embedded in expectations, making eventual adjustment more costly.",
