    more: "When unemployment is low, wage pressure and demand are high, pushing inflation up. When unemployment is high, slack in labor markets suppresses wages and prices. The short-run Phillips curve shifts when inflation expectations change: higher expected inflation shifts the curve upward, requiring higher unemployment to achieve any given inflation rate.",
    detailed: "The original Phillips curve (1958) showed a stable empirical relationship between wage inflation and unemployment in the UK. In the 1970s, the curve shifted upward as inflation expectations rose following oil shocks and accommodative monetary policy, producing stagflation that the original model could not explain. Friedman and Phelps argued the curve was only stable in the short run at any given level of expected inflation; in the long run, workers and firms adjust expectations, making the trade-off illusory. The short-run Phillips curve remains useful for understanding why central banks face a short-run cost in employment when disinflating. Common mistake: Students treat the short-run Phillips curve as a permanent, exploitable policy trade-off. It is only stable at a given level of inflation expectations; attempts to exploit it persistently shift the curve upward as expectations adjust.",
