    detailed: "The LRPC represents the natural rate hypothesis advanced by Friedman and Phelps: the economy gravitates to the natural rate of unemployment regardless of the inflation rate, once expectations have fully adjusted. This underpins the modern consensus that the Federal Reserve's role is to deliver low and stable inflation, not to permanently hold unemployment below NAIRU. If the Fed tries to exploit the short-run trade-off by keeping rates low indefinitely, it simply shifts the short-run Phillips curve upward as expectations rise, arriving at the same unemployment rate but with higher inflation. Common mistake: Students conflate the short-run and long-run Phillips curves. The downward-sloping relationship is only temporary; the long-run curve is vertical, meaning there is no permanent trade-off to exploit through sustained expansionary policy.",
